hey discuss their life's work: understanding the what, when, and how of the early evolution of life on Earth. Presented in nontechnical language and including a useful glossary of scientific terms, Life's Origin gives a state-of-the-art encapsulation of the fascinating work now being done by scientists as they begin to characterize life as a natural outcome of the evolution of cosmic matter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLifexOrigin. 0aMolecular evolution. 7aSCIENCE / Paleontology.2bisacsh  aamino acids.  aancient world.  abig bang.  abiological evolution.  abiological.  abiology.  abiotic.  acomets.  adna.  aevolution.  aextraterrestrial.  afossil record.  ahistory of life.  ahuman biology.  ahuman evolution.  ahypotheses.  aliving organism.  ameteorite.  aorigin of life.  aprebiotic.  aresearch.  arna.  ascience.  ascientific history.  ascientific.  asolar system.  asupernova.  atree of life.  aworld history.1 aChang, Sherwood, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerris, James P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazcano, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Stanley L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrgel, Leslie E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOró, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchopf, J. William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchopf, J. William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchwartz, Alan W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Pack